Schutte   ‘archer’.","English: nickname for a short person, from Middle English <i>scut(e)</i> ‘short’, or else for a swift runner, from Middle English <i>scut</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Kyong, Kyong Suk, Young, Chae, Chi Young, Hang, Kil, Rin, Sang Hun, Chang, Chong, Insoo, Kum, Sun Young, Yom, Young Hwan.  Cambodian Kiwan, Oeurn, Phoeun, Pich, Saroeuth, Seung, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Scott Of Rankilburn was born in 1378, in Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Robert Scott 3rd Of Rankilburn and Unknown Scott. He had at least 1 son with Lady Telfer. He died in 1426, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1378–1426":"1378–1426","–Female":"Surnud","1394–1469":"1394–1469","1335–1389":"1335–1389","1426":"1426","1469":"1469","1335":"1335","1378":"1378","1389":"1389","1394":"1394","about 1394":"umbes 1394","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1378–1426":"1378–1426","–Female":"Kuollut","1394–1469":"1394–1469","1335–1389":"1335–1389","1426":"1426","1469":"1469","1335":"1335","1378":"1378","1389":"1389","1394":"1394","about 1394":"noin 1394","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1378–1426":"1378–1426","–Female":"Décédée","1394–1469":"1394–1469","1335–1389":"1335–1389","1426":"1426","1469":"1469","1335":"1335","1378":"1378","1389":"1389","1394":"1394","about 1394":"environ 1394","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Robert Scott Of Rankilburn est né en 1378, à Écosse, Royaume-Uni, fils de Robert Scott 3rd Of Rankilburn et Unknown Scott. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Lady Telfer. Il est décédé en 1426, à l’âge de 48 ans."},"de":{"1378–1426":"1378–1426","–Female":"Verstorben","1394–1469":"1394–1469","1335–1389":"1335–1389","1426":"1426","1469":"1469","1335":"1335","1378":"1378","1389":"1389","1394":"1394","about 1394":"um 1394","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Schottland, United Kingdom